article.description:
Wang ZhiZhi scored a career-high 21 pointsand rookie Marko Jaric scored nine of his 13 points during a 3:45
span of the fourth quarter as the Los Angeles Clippers' bench did most of the damage in a 91-78 victory over the Denver Nuggets on Wednesday.
article.headline: Wang's career-high 21 fuels Clippers' victory
article.linkText: Wang enjoys career night in leading Clippers past Denver
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Ten games into his stint as interim coach of the Los Angeles Clippers, Dennis Johnson is trying to impress management enough to keep him next season. So he isn't too particular about who the wins are coming against. Wang ZhiZhi scored a career-high 21 points, and rookie Marko Jaric had nine of his 13 points during a 3:45 span of the fourth quarter as the Los Angeles bench did most of the damage in a 91-78 victory over the dreadful Denver Nuggets on Wednesday night. Lamar Odom added 13 points for the Clippers, who won for only the sixth time in 27 games and are 3-7 since Johnson replaced Alvin Gentry as head coach on March 3. Their three victories have come against teams that are currently a combined 79-144, including Chicago (24-45) and Toronto (21-45). "As I told the guys, we have to win the games on the schedule that look like we can win,'' Johnson said. "I just want them to keep playing the same way they've been playing. "When guys don't play well, you make substitutions, and I did. The second group picked up the first group, and we kept going from there.'' One night after losing at Utah for the 14th straight time, the Nuggets (14-54) lost on the Clippers' home court for the sixth consecutive time. Juwan Howard led Denver with 24 points. The Clippers ran off nine straight points to increase a six-point lead to 57-42. Odom and Eric Piatkowski hit 3-pointers during the run. "They hit the shots. We didn't play well at all,'' Marcus Camby said. "Everybody on their team played well. Even the bench players put up points.'' Denver's Chris Andersen, a 57.5-percent free-throw shooter, brought derisive cheers from the crowd of 15,590 when he airballed a foul shot with three minutes left in the third. The Nuggets got no closer than nine points with 8:16 to play due to Jaric's late scoring binge. "Once again, it's our inability to shoot the basketball from the floor to the free throw line,'' coach Jeff Bzdelik said after watching his team miss 10 of 22 from the line. Bzdelik used his 25th different starting lineup, giving oft-injured Camby his second start in 17 games this season. Shammond Williams started for the first time in 13 games since being acquired from Boston in a Feb. 20 trade for Mark Blount and Mark Bryant. He was 3-for-11 with 9 points in 31 minutes. Wang, who led the Clippers in scoring for the first time since signing with them as a free agent in October, powered Los Angeles to a 41-34 halftime lead with 11 points. "All guys want is an opportunity to play,'' Piatkowski said. "Right now we really have two people at every position because of injuries and there aren't any guys going out there playing 40-45 minutes. "So when you get an opportunity to contribute, you play harder out there. Obviously, a lot of guys are happy right now.'' The highlight of the first half came when 6-foot-6 guard Quentin Richardson slam-dunked over 6-foot-11 rookie Nene Hilario with 3:06 left in the second quarter, capping a 12-4 run that increased the Clippers' lead to 39-30. Two minutes earlier, Hilario's attempted layup was blocked by Clippers rookie Chris Wilcox. "The big challenge was to come out after halftime and continue what we were doing,'' Johnson said. "The first five minutes of the third quarter are very important. You need to come out and be a really aggressive team, and we're learning to do that.'' Nuggets rookie forward Vincent Yarbrough left the game after spraining his right ankle with 9:24 left in the second quarter.

Game notes
The opening tip was delayed because of President Bush's speech signaling the start of the war against Iraq. Richardson and Wilcox wore red, white and blue headbands during the game, instead of their customary red ones. ... Staples Center again served as a haven for NBA teams that play in a cities where snowfalls have been measured in feet instead of inches. The Nuggets missed Denver's worst blizzard in 90 years. On Feb. 15, the Clippers hosted the Celtics while a storm was dumping 17 inches on Boston. One day later, the Knicks played the Lakers here as New Yorkers dug out from 19.8 inches. ... Denver would have to go 6-8 the rest of the way to avoid finishing with fewer than 20 wins for the second time in franchise history in an 82-game season.
